.TH "nla_strscpy" 9 "nla_strscpy" "May 2021" "Kernel Hacker's Manual" LINUX
.SH NAME
nla_strscpy \- Copy string attribute payload into a sized buffer
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B "ssize_t" nla_strscpy
.BI "(char *dst "  ","
.BI "const struct nlattr *nla "  ","
.BI "size_t dstsize "  ");"
.SH ARGUMENTS
.IP "dst" 12
Where to copy the string to.
.IP "nla" 12
Attribute to copy the string from.
.IP "dstsize" 12
Size of destination buffer.
.SH "DESCRIPTION"
Copies at most dstsize - 1 bytes into the destination buffer.
Unlike strlcpy the destination buffer is always padded out.
.SH "RETURN"
* srclen - Returns \fInla\fP length (not including the trailing NUL).
* -E2BIG - If \fIdstsize\fP is 0 or greater than U16_MAX or \fInla\fP length greater
than \fIdstsize\fP.
